<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Eugene L. Roberts Jr., who announced July 31 that he was stepping down as 
executive editor of the Philadelphia Inquirer, will become a professor in the 
College of Journalism at the University of Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
Roberts, 58, is one of the country's most honored newspaper editors. His paper 
won 17 Pulitzer Prizes during his 18-year tenure. Before that, Roberts was 
national editor, a Vietnam War correspondent and Southern correspondent for the 
New York Times. He will join the Maryland faculty in September, 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
