<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE: FUTURES EXCHANGE HEAD NOT SURE IF HE'LL STAY ON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After only a month as chairman of the Chicago Board of Trade, William F. 
O'Connor is not sure whether he wants to remain at the helm of the world's 
largest futures exchange. 
</P>
<P>
O'Connor, 55, said he hasn't decided whether he wants to serve beyond January, 
when his term expires. 
</P>
<P>
O'Connor was appointed chairman July 31 when Karsten (Cash) Mahlmann resigned 
amid financial woes at Stotler Group Inc., a futures brokerage firm of which he 
was also chairman. 
</P>
<P>
"I ran for election for vice chairman, and I became chairman by a means which I 
didn't want to become chairman," O'Connor said. "I still don't know if I want 
to be chairman." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, William F. O'Connor Associated Press 
</P>
