<HEADLINE>
<P>
JENNY CRAIG DENIES CLOSING BRITISH CLINICS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS KRAUL, SAN DIEGO COUNTY BUSINESS EDITOR 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jenny Craig Inc., the Del Mar-based operator and franchiser of weight-loss 
centers, Wednesday disputed a British newspaper report that 33 of its centers 
in the United Kingdom had closed down because of financial problems of the 
British franchisee running them. 
</P>
<P>
In its Tuesday Editions, the Today newspaper reported that 33 Jenny Craig 
clinics, all situated in the greater London area, "went bust" this week because 
of "massive debts." 
</P>
<P>
Weight-loss clients -- the newspaper described them as "shocked slimmers" -- 
were informed of the closings in telephone calls Sept. 3. Many had already paid 
the $335 annual fee that the centers charge, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
Jenny Craig Inc. spokesman Phillip Myers denied Wednesday that the centers had 
closed, but said closures are "being contemplated." He acknowledged that the 
company's British franchisee, Jenny Craig Weight Loss Centres (U.K.) Ltd., and 
its managing director, Jeremy Beloff, were having financial problems. The U.K. 
centers have been open about three years. 
</P>
<P>
"It's undecided whether (the centers) are going to stay open or close. The 
franchisee is reviewing his operations," Myers said. "There have been some 
market challenges in the U.K. . . . This is an unusual situation for Jenny." 
</P>
<P>
Myers declined to discuss what the company's options are if the United Kingdom 
operation was too fail. 
</P>
<P>
The Jenny Craig Weight Loss Centres chain has grown rapidly since its founding 
in 1982 by wife and husband, Jenny and Sid Craig. System-wide revenues will 
reach $500 million in 1990, or double last year's sales, Myers said. 
</P>
<P>
The centers, which offer weekly weight-watching classes and sell low-calorie 
packaged diet foods, now total 570 in the U.S., Australia and the United 
Kingdom. The number of U.S outlets has grown to 433 from just 14 in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
The company, which owns 70% of its centers, has been rapidly gaining on 
industry leaders Nutri/System and Diet Centers, each of which have more than 
1,000 storefronts. Company officials have said they expect 1,000 Jenny Craig 
Weight Loss Centres to be open in the United States alone by the end of 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
