<HEADLINE>
<P>
COOK IT LIGHT: PEANUT BUTTER COOKIES WITHOUT THE CHOLESTEROL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANNE JONES, Jones is a food consultant and a cookbook author. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The recipe for this tasty, sugar-free cookie was sent to me by a reader. I have 
revised it slightly to make it cholesterol-free as well. 
</P>
<P>
It is easy to make and ideal for brown-bag lunches. It is also a wonderfully 
healthful after-school snack. 
</P>
<P>
SOFT PEANUT-BUTTER COOKIES 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup raisins 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup chopped dates, packed 
</P>
<P>
1 ripe medium banana, mashed 
</P>
<P>
1/3 cup unhomogenized creamy peanut butter 
</P>
<P>
1/4 cup water 
</P>
<P>
2 egg whites 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon vanilla 
</P>
<P>
1 cup oats 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup whole-wheat flour 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon baking soda 
</P>
<P>
In mixing bowl combine raisins, dates, banana, peanut butter, water, egg whites 
and vanilla. Beat until blended. Add oats, flour and baking soda. Mix to blend 
thoroughly. 
</P>
<P>
Drop by heaping teaspoons onto non-stick baking sheet. Bake at 350 degrees 
about 10 minutes or until browned on underside. Cool on rack. Store in airtight 
container. Makes about 50 cookies. 
</P>
<P>
 Each cookie contains approximately 32 calories; no cholesterol; 1 gm fat; 17 
mg sodium. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
