<HEADLINE>
<P>
EX-SAN DIEGO MAYOR WINS RETRIAL ON PERJURY CHARGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former San Diego Mayor Roger Hedgecock, forced from office after being 
convicted of hiding campaign contributions, won a new trial today from the 
state Supreme Court on his 12 perjury convictions. 
</P>
<P>
The court also set aside Hedgecock's remaining conviction, for conspiracy to 
violate campaign disclosure laws, to let a San Diego judge consider allegations 
that a bailiff improperly influenced jurors by talking about the case and 
providing them with liquor. 
</P>
<P>
In 1985, Hedgecock was convicted of failing to disclose more than $350,000 in 
contributions to his successful 1983 campaign for mayor. The money allegedly 
came from principals in J. David &amp; Co., an investment firm that later 
collapsed. Prosecutors said some of the contributions violated local election 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
Hedgecock's one-year jail sentence and $1,000 fine have been stayed during his 
appeal. He now works as a San Diego radio talk show host. 
</P>
<P>
Hedgecock, 44, said today that he is confident the ruling "is going to be the 
beginning of setting the record straight on this pretty unfortunate episode in 
my life and the life of San Diego." 
</P>
<P>
The former mayor had contended that he was guilty of no more than bad 
bookkeeping and claimed that he was the target of a vendetta by Dist. Atty. 
Edwin Miller. 
</P>
<P>
Hedgecock said a retrial would be "a horrifying waste of resources (and) time." 
Miller's office had no immediate comment on the ruling or on whether a retrial 
would be sought; a news conference was scheduled for later in the day. 
</P>
<P>
The court voted, 4 to 3, to overturn the perjury convictions on the ground that 
then-Superior Court Judge William Todd told the jury that the alleged 
deliberate errors and omissions in Hedgecock's campaign finance reports were 
"material," or substantial enough to support perjury charges. 
</P>
<P>
Whether the inaccuracies were material was a factual question to be decided by 
the jury, the Supreme Court opinion by Justice Joyce Kennard said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA090690-0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 272731 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 6, 1990, Thursday, P.M. Final 
</P>
</DATE>
